<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="116" name="Solutions">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>A homogeneous mixture of two or more substances is called a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solution</option><option id="B">Suspension</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uniform distribution of solute in solvent.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In a binary solution, the component present in larger quantity is the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solvent</option><option id="B">Solute</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Determines the physical state of the solution.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The component of a solution which is present in smaller quantity is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solute</option><option id="B">Solvent</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dissolved in the solvent.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of moles of solute per litre of solution is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molarity</option><option id="B">Molality</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Concentration term based on volume.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of moles of solute per kilogram of solvent is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molality</option><option id="B">Molarity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Temperature independent concentration term.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of mole fractions of all components in a solution is always ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It is a dimensionless ratio total.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following concentration terms depends on temperature?</text>
            <option id="A">Molarity</option><option id="B">Molality</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Volume changes with temperature, but mass does not.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of gases in liquids generally ____ with increase in temperature.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dissolution of gas is usually exothermic.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of gases in liquids ____ with increase in pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Described by Henry's Law.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Henry's Law constant (Kh) ____ with increase in temperature.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>P = Kh * x; higher Kh means lower solubility.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of a gas in vapor phase is proportional to its mole fraction in solution. This is ____ Law.</text>
            <option id="A">Henry's</option><option id="B">Raoult's</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental gas solubility law.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Raoult's Law states that for volatile liquids, P1 = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">x1 * P1°</option><option id="B">x1 / P1°</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relation between vapor pressure and mole fraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solutions which obey Raoult's Law over the entire range of concentrations are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ideal solutions</option><option id="B">Non-ideal solutions</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Interactions A-B are same as A-A and B-B.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>For an ideal solution, the enthalpy of mixing (ΔHmix) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No heat is evolved or absorbed.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>For an ideal solution, the volume change on mixing (ΔVmix) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Particles occupy the same space as in pure components.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which mixture forms an nearly ideal solution?</text>
            <option id="A">n-Hexane and n-Heptane</option><option id="B">Ethanol and Acetone</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar molecular sizes and structures.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Large positive deviation from Raoult's Law leads to ____ boiling azeotropes.</text>
            <option id="A">Minimum</option><option id="B">Maximum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Total vapor pressure is higher than expected.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Large negative deviation from Raoult's Law leads to ____ boiling azeotropes.</text>
            <option id="A">Maximum</option><option id="B">Minimum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Total vapor pressure is lower than expected.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Colligative properties depend only on the ____ of solute particles.</text>
            <option id="A">Number</option><option id="B">Nature</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Independent of the identity of the solute.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is NOT a colligative property?</text>
            <option id="A">Boiling point</option><option id="B">Osmotic pressure</option><option id="C">Elevation in boiling point</option><option id="D">Relative lowering of vapor pressure</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>The property is 'elevation' in boiling point, not the point itself.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The relative lowering of vapor pressure is equal to the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mole fraction of solute</option><option id="B">Molarity of solute</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(P1° - P1) / P1° = x2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling point elevation formula is ΔTb = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kb * m</option><option id="B">Kb / m</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dependent on molality.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Freezing point depression formula is ΔTf = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kf * m</option><option id="B">Kf / m</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dependent on molality.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Flow of solvent through semi-permeable membrane into solution is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Osmosis</option><option id="B">Diffusion</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Driven by concentration gradient.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Osmotic pressure formula is pi = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CRT</option><option id="B">CRT / V</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C is molar concentration.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solutions having same osmotic pressure at a given temperature are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Isotonic</option><option id="B">Hypotonic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No net osmosis between them.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reverse osmosis requires applied pressure to be ____ than osmotic pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Greater</option><option id="B">Lesser</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forces solvent through membrane from solution.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Van't Hoff factor (i) for association is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">&lt; 1</option><option id="B">> 1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Number of particles decreases.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Van't Hoff factor (i) for dissociation is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">> 1</option><option id="B">&lt; 1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Number of particles increases.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The value of i for NaCl in a dilute solution is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NaCl dissociates into Na+ and Cl-.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The value of i for glucose is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Non-electrolyte; does not dissociate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of ebullioscopic constant (Kb) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">K kg / mol</option><option id="B">mol / kg</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from formula ΔTb / m.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of solids in liquids with increase in temperature usually ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases (if endothermic)</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most salts show this behavior.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Low oxygen in climbers' blood at high altitude is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Anoxia</option><option id="B">Bends</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Result of low atmospheric partial pressure of O2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogen bubbles in scuba divers' blood is a condition called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bends</option><option id="B">Anoxia</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Avoided by diluting air with Helium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of gas in vapor phase is p = Kh * ____.</text>
            <option id="A">x</option><option id="B">C</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>x is the mole fraction in solution.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A mixture of 95% ethanol and 5% water is a ____ azeotrope.</text>
            <option id="A">Minimum boiling</option><option id="B">Maximum boiling</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows large positive deviation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A mixture of nitric acid and water is a ____ azeotrope.</text>
            <option id="A">Maximum boiling</option><option id="B">Minimum boiling</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows large negative deviation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Molecular mass of macromolecules (proteins) is best determined by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Osmotic pressure</option><option id="B">Boiling point elevation</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measurable at room temp; higher magnitude.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethylene glycol is used in car radiators as an ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Antifreeze</option><option id="B">Oxidant</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lowers the freezing point of water.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of a 1M aqueous solution of glucose?</text>
            <option id="A">Non-electrolyte; i = 1</option><option id="B">Strong electrolyte; i = 2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Glucose does not ionize in water.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between Kh and temperature is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kh increases with temperature</option><option id="B">Kh decreases with temperature</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher temperature implies lower gas solubility.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A non-ideal solution with positive deviation from Raoult's Law has ΔHmix ____ 0.</text>
            <option id="A">> (Endothermic)</option><option id="B">&lt; (Exothermic)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy absorbed to break A-A and B-B bonds.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A non-ideal solution with negative deviation from Raoult's Law has ΔVmix ____ 0.</text>
            <option id="A">&lt; (Contraction)</option><option id="B">> (Expansion)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stronger A-B attractions pull molecules closer.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mixing Chloroform and Acetone results in ____ deviation.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydrogen bonding (C-H...O) occurs between components.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mixing Ethanol and Acetone results in ____ deviation.</text>
            <option id="A">Positive</option><option id="B">Negative</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Breaks the hydrogen bonds present in pure ethanol.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Colligative properties depend on the relative number of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solute particles</option><option id="B">Solvent molecules</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Independent of the nature of particles.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The mole fraction of water in a 1.0 m aqueous solution is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.982</option><option id="B">1.0</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</explanation>1 / (1 + 1000/18) = 1 / 56.5 = 0.0177; 1 - 0.0177 = 0.982.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>For a dilute solution, the lowering of vapor pressure equals ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mole fraction of solute</option><option id="B">Pressure difference</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ΔP / P° = x2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Values of Kb and Kf depend only on the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solvent</option><option id="B">Solute</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constants for a given medium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Calculating molar mass (M2) from ΔTb: M2 = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(Kb * w2 * 1000) / (ΔTb * w1)</option><option id="B">(ΔTb * w1) / (Kb * w2)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>w2 = mass solute, w1 = mass solvent.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Calculation of i for K2SO4 (complete dissociation): i = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 K+ and 1 SO4 2- ions produced.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Calculation of i for K4[Fe(CN)6] (complete dissociation): i = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>4 K+ and 1 Complex anion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Association of acetic acid in benzene occurs due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen bonding (Dimerization)</option><option id="B">Ionic attraction</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Molar mass observed becomes nearly double (i=0.5).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isosmotic solutions must have the same ____ at same T.</text>
            <option id="A">Molar concentration</option><option id="B">Mass</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Assuming i=1 for both.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal saline used in injections is ____% (w/v) NaCl.</text>
            <option id="A">0.9</option><option id="B">1.0</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Isotonic with human blood cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Flow of water into RBCs placed in distilled water causes them to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Swell / Burst</option><option id="B">Shrink</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hypotonic environment.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of too much salt in body tissues causes ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Edema</option><option id="B">Anemia</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water retention via osmosis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Equation relating pi to h, rho, g: pi = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h * rho * g</option><option id="B">h / (rho * g)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydrostatic pressure balance in osmometer.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Raoult's Law becomes a special case of Henry's Law when ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kh = P1°</option><option id="B">P1 = P1°</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constants match.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mole fraction of ethylene glycol in solution of 20% by mass is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.068</option><option id="B">0.2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(20/62) / [(20/62) + (80/18)].</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Molarity of pure water (d=1g/mL) is ____ M.</text>
            <option id="A">55.5</option><option id="B">18</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(1000 / 18) moles per liter.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The unit of Henry's Law constant (Kh) can be ____.</text>
            <option id="A">atm / bar</option><option id="B">Dimensionless</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Matching units of partial pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If dissolution is endothermic, solubility ____ with temperature.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>According to Le Chatelier's Principle.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vapor pressure of a liquid increases with increase in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Temperature</option><option id="B">Surface Area</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases kinetic energy of molecules.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Elevation in boiling point is a ____ property.</text>
            <option id="A">Colligative</option><option id="B">Chemical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Depends on number of solute particles.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ebullioscopic constant is also called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molal elevation constant</option><option id="B">Depression constant</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kb definition.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cryoscopic constant is also called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molal depression constant</option><option id="B">Elevation constant</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kf definition.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Osmotic pressure is independent of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nature of non-volatile solute</option><option id="B">Temperature</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It is a colligative property.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ideal solutions show ΔAmix equal to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ΔSmix > 0 (always true for mixing)</option><option id="B">ΔGmix = 0 (false)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mixing increases disorder.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vapor pressure of water at 100 °C is ____ bar.</text>
            <option id="A">1.013</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard atmospheric pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzene and Toluene form an ____ solution.</text>
            <option id="A">Ideal</option><option id="B">Non-ideal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar structures and interactions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which concentration term is most suitable for gas-liquid solutions?</text>
            <option id="A">Mole fraction</option><option id="B">Molarity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used directly in Henry's Law.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of a solution is 1.2 g/mL. Mass % is 20%. Molarity is ____ d.</text>
            <option id="A">Calculation needed (approx 1.3M for H2SO4 etc)</option><option id="B">Constant</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>M = (mass% * 10 * d) / MolarMass.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which setup is used for desalination of seawater?</text>
            <option id="A">Reverse Osmosis units</option><option id="B">Simple filters</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Drives water through membrane under pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The value of pi for a 1M solution at 300K is approx ____ atm.</text>
            <option id="A">24.6 (1 * 0.0821 * 300)</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>pi = MRT computation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Semi-permeable membrane allows ____ to pass but not ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solvent, Solute</option><option id="B">Solute, Solvent</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on particle size / nature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Is molarity changes with temperature?</text>
